<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>How Scoring Works</title>
{% include "_style.html.j2" %}
</head>
<body>
<a class="back" href="index.html">&larr; All cities</a>
<h1>How Scoring Works</h1>

<p class="overall-summary">
Every city gets two independent fit scores, not one blended number: <strong>Family Fit</strong>
(day-to-day life for the family) and <strong>Self-Sufficiency</strong> (homestead/resilience
concerns). A city can score well on one and poorly on the other &mdash; that tension is shown,
not averaged away. Numeric fields are scored <strong>relative to the cities actually
evaluated</strong> (the cheapest home price in the set scores highest, not against some fixed
"good" price), so scores can shift slightly as new cities are added. This page is generated
directly from <code>preferences.json</code> &mdash; if the weights below ever change, this page
updates itself.
</p>

{% for lens in lenses %}
<details class="category" open>
  <summary>{{ lens.label }} &mdash; category weights</summary>
  <table class="field-table field-table--fields">
    <tr><th>Category</th><th>Weight</th><th></th></tr>
    {% for cat in lens.categories %}
    <tr>
      <td class="field-label">{{ cat.label }}</td>
      <td>{{ cat.tier }}</td>
      <td class="source-link">{{ cat.weight }}x</td>
    </tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </table>
  {% if lens.dealbreakers %}
  <p><strong>Dealbreakers</strong> for this lens &mdash; any one of these overrides the score
  entirely, regardless of everything else:</p>
  <ul>
    {% for db in lens.dealbreakers %}<li>{{ db }}</li>{% endfor %}
  </ul>
  {% else %}
  <p class="caveat">No dealbreakers for this lens.</p>
  {% endif %}
</details>
{% endfor %}

<details class="category" open>
  <summary>Shared rules</summary>
  <p><strong>Risk severity fields</strong> (wildfire/flood/earthquake risk, homeschool and
  permitting strictness, etc.) are read from free text and mapped to a score:</p>
  <table class="field-table field-table--fields">
    <tr><th>Level</th><th>Score</th></tr>
    <tr><td class="field-label">Low</td><td>{{ risk_severity_scores.low }}</td><td></td></tr>
    <tr><td class="field-label">Moderate</td><td>{{ risk_severity_scores.moderate }}</td><td></td></tr>
    <tr><td class="field-label">High</td><td>{{ risk_severity_scores.high }}</td><td></td></tr>
  </table>

  <p><strong>Final label</strong>, from the 0-100 internal score (only the label is shown on
  reports, not the number):</p>
  <table class="field-table field-table--fields">
    <tr><th>Score</th><th>Label</th><th></th></tr>
    {% for tier in label_thresholds %}
    <tr><td class="field-label">{{ tier.min }}+</td><td>{{ tier.label }}</td><td></td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </table>

  <p><strong>Missing data:</strong> a category with some unresolved fields is scored on just
  the fields that do have data &mdash; a gap narrows what's being measured, it doesn't count
  against the city.</p>
</details>

<details class="category">
  <summary>Fields not included in any score</summary>
  <p class="caveat">
  Still shown in every report, just not counted &mdash; either no reliable "better/worse"
  direction (population, hardiness zone), or free-text legal/regulatory fields with no
  controlled vocabulary to classify against yet (carry law, firearm restrictions, well
  legality, raw dairy legality, and similar).
  </p>
  {% for cat in unscored_fields %}
  <p><strong>{{ cat.category_label }}:</strong> {{ cat.fields | join(", ") }}</p>
  {% endfor %}
</details>

</body>
</html>
